een conducted in two separate arenas: majority language contexts involving international languages, such as English, French, Spanish and Portuguese, and minority community contexts aimed at maintaining native Amerindian languages as well as the different Sign Languages of the South American Deaf communities. This book presents an integrated vision of bilingual education in six South American nations: three Andean countries, Peru, Ecuador, and Colombia, and three ‘Southern Cone’ countries, Brazil, Argentina and Paraguay. It includes work carried out in minority as well as majority language contexts, referring to developments in the fields of indigenous, Deaf, and international bilingual and multilingual provision.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBilingualismxCross-cultural studiesxSouth America. 0aBilingualismzSouth AmericavCross-cultural studies. 0aEducation, BilingualxCross-cultural studiesxSouth America. 0aEducation, BilingualzSouth AmericavCross-cultural studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSouth America.  abilingual education.  alanguage education.1 aBanfi, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, María Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Kendall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMejía, Anne-Marie de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrdóñez, Claudia Lucía, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQuadros, Ronice Muller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, JoEllen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkliar, Carlos, 